2.1 Preliminary Notes

Data Quality Issues

We observe some suspicious patterns in the data that are currently pending a more detailed investigation. These findings should be taken with more grains of salt than advised in the section introduction.

  • What we see in the data is a broad pattern of low satisfaction with employment services
  • If we take the responses at face value, they paint a picture of a system that troubling portions of its clients neither understand, feel understood by, trust, nor find effective
  • At a glance, we see that newcomers, youth, and Indigenous clients have particularly less positive experiences

2.2 Respondent Characteristics

2.2.1 Inclusion Group Representation

Table 2.1 shows the representation of inclusion groups among client survey respondents.

Show code 
dplt_client_ig <- d_long_raw |> 
    group_by(inclusion_group_label) |>
    summarize(
        N = n(),
        n = sum(ig_member),
        p = n / N
    ) |>
    mutate(
        pn = glue::glue("{scales::percent(p, accuracy = 1)} ({n}/{N})")
    ) |>
    arrange(desc(p)) 

dplt_client_ig |>
    select(inclusion_group_label, sample_representation = pn) |>
    arrange(inclusion_group_label) |> 
    gt() |>
    gtExtras::gt_theme_538() |>
    tab_source_note(
        source_note = dl_button(dplt_client_ig, "xp-client-igo")
    )

Figure 2.1 shows the representation of each pair of inclusion groups among client survey respondents. Pairwise, the most common intersections we see are racialized newcomers, newcomers receiving social assistance, racialized francopohones, and francophone newcomers.

Show code 
dplt_ig_int <- d_long_raw |> 
    filter(ig_short != "[Z]") |> 
    select(response_id, ig_x = ig_short, val_x = ig_member) |> 
    filter(!is.na(val_x)) %>%
    left_join(
        rename(., ig_y = ig_x, val_y = val_x),
        by = "response_id",
        relationship = "many-to-many"
    ) |>
    group_by(ig_x, ig_y) |>
    summarize(
        N = n(),
        n = sum(val_x * val_y),
        p = mean(val_x * val_y)
    )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'ig_x'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.

2.2.2 Demographics

Table 2.2 summarizes gender, parenthood, and age: the demographic characteristics included in the client survey but not reflected in the inclusion group indicator variables.

Show code 
tbl_key_demos <- d_long |> 
    group_by(inclusion_group_label) |>
    summarize(
        p_woman_plus = mean(demo_gender != "Man", na.rm = TRUE),
        p_parent = mean(demo_parent, na.rm = TRUE),
        mean_age = mean(demo_age, na.rm = TRUE),
        age_dist = list(demo_age),
    )

reactable(
    tbl_key_demos,
    columns = list(
        p_woman_plus = colDef(
            cell = function(value) {
                scales::percent(value, accuracy = 1)
            }
        ),
        p_parent = colDef(
            cell = function(value) {
                scales::percent(value, accuracy = 1)
            }
        ),
        mean_age = colDef(
            cell = function(value) {
                round(value, 1)
            }
        ),
        age_dist = colDef(
            cell = function(values) {
                sparkline(
                    values,
                    type = "box",
                    chartRangeMin = min(d$demo_age, na.rm = TRUE),
                    chartRangeMax = max(d$demo_age, na.rm = TRUE)
                )
            }
        )
    )
)

2.2.3 Education

Figure 2.2 shows the education level of client survey respondents by inclusion group. At each level of education, the split between domestic and international education is shown in the fill colour.

Show code 
tbl_educ <- d_long |> 
    filter(
        !is.na(demo_education),
        !is.na(demo_educ_domestic)
    ) |>
    group_by(inclusion_group = ig_short, demo_education, demo_educ_domestic) |>
    summarize(
        n = n(),
        .groups = "drop_last"
    ) |>
    group_by(inclusion_group) |>
    mutate(
        p = n / sum(n)
    )

tbl_educ |>
    ggplot(aes(p, demo_education, fill = demo_educ_domestic)) +
    geom_col(position = "stack") +
    facet_wrap(~inclusion_group, nrow = 2) +
    scale_fill_blueprint(discrete = TRUE, type = "bipolar", option = "blue_green") +
    theme_blueprint(base_size = 12, grid = "Xx") +
    scale_x_continuous(
        labels = scales::percent_format(accuracy = 1),
        limits = c(0, .5),
        expand = c(0, 0)
    )

Figure 2.3 is based on the same data as Figure 2.2, but rather than showing the proportion of respondents at each level of education, it shows the proportion of respondents who have achieved at least each level of education.

Show code 
tbl_educ_ecdf <- tbl_educ |>
    arrange(desc(demo_education)) |>
    group_by(inclusion_group, demo_educ_domestic) |>
    mutate(
        ecdf = cumsum(p)
    )


tbl_educ_ecdf |>
    ggplot(aes(ecdf, demo_education, fill = demo_educ_domestic)) +

    facet_wrap(~inclusion_group, nrow = 2) +

2.2.4 Labour Force Status

Table 2.3 shows the labour force status of client survey respondents by inclusion group. The employment rate is the proportion of respondents who are employed, the enrollment rate is the proportion of respondents who are enrolled in education, and the NEET rate is the proportion of respondents who are not in employment, education, or training. The median annualized earnings are shown alongside the distribution of annualized earnings, visualized as a box plot for each inclusion group.

Sussy Data Alert!!

Self-reported employment rates and annualized earnings are shockingly high for respondents who also self-reported having received payments from OW or ODSP in the past two weeks.

Show code 
tbl_emp <- d |>
    mutate(lfs_neet = !(lfs_employed | lfs_educ_enrolled)) |>
    pivot_longer(
        matches("^ig_"),
        names_to = "inclusion_group",
        values_to = "val"
    ) |>
    filter(val) |>
    mutate(inclusion_group = unlist(labs[inclusion_group])) |>
    group_by(inclusion_group) |>
    summarize(
        employment_rate = mean(lfs_employed, na.rm = TRUE),
        enrollment_rate = mean(lfs_educ_enrolled, na.rm = TRUE),
        neet_rate = mean(lfs_neet, na.rm = TRUE),
        median_annualized_earnings = median(job_annualized_earnings_total, na.rm = TRUE),
        annualized_earnings = list(na.omit(job_annualized_earnings_total))
    )

tbl_emp |>
    reactable(
        columns = list(
            employment_rate = colDef(
                cell = function(value) {
                    scales::percent(value, accuracy = 1)
                }
            ),
            enrollment_rate = colDef(
                cell = function(value) {
                    scales::percent(value, accuracy = 1)
                }
            ),
            neet_rate = colDef(
                cell = function(value) {
                    scales::percent(value, accuracy = 1)
                }
            ),
            median_annualized_earnings = colDef(
                format = colFormat(currency = "USD", separators = TRUE)
            ),
            annualized_earnings = colDef(
                cell = function(values) {
                    sparkline(
                        values,
                        type = "box",
                        chartRangeMin = 0,
                        chartRangeMax = 2.5e5
                    )
                }
            )
        )
    )

2.3.5 Job Precarity

Table 2.7 summarizes the proportion of employed respondents who reported that their primary job was casual, seasonal, or temporary by inclusion group. The most common form of precarity reported is casual employment, making up 45% of primary jobs across the sample. Across each measure of precarity, social assistance recipients reported the highest rates.

Show code 
t_job_sat <- d_long |> 
    filter(lfs_employed) |> 
    pivot_longer(matches("^job_is_.*_primary"), names_to = "var", values_to = "val") |>
    group_by(ig_short, var) |> 
    summarize(
        p = mean(val, na.rm = TRUE)
    )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'ig_short'. You can override using the
`.groups` argument.
Show code 
t_job_sat |> 
    pivot_wider(names_from = ig_short, values_from = p) |> 
    mutate(
        lab = case_when(
            var |> str_detect("casual") ~ "Casual", 
            var |> str_detect("seasonal") ~ "Seasonal", 
            var |> str_detect("temporary") ~ "Temporary"
        )
    ) |> 
    select(-var) |> 
    select(lab, everything()) |>  
    gt() |> 
    gtExtras::gt_theme_538() |>

    )

2.3.7 Job Satisfaction

Table 2.9 summarizes net agreement1 with three statements concerning primary job2 satisfaction among employed respondents by inclusion group. We see evidence of higher overall job satisfaction among social assistance recipients and youth. Social assistance recipients are particularly interesting here, as they were both the most optimistic group with respect to advancement opportunities whilst also being the most concerned about job precarity. Indigenous respondents reported roughly average levels of overall satisfaction, but were by quite a wide margin the least optimistic about advancement opportunities.

Show code 
t_job_sat <- d_long |> 
    filter(lfs_employed) |> 
    pivot_longer(matches("^job_sat_.*_primary"), names_to = "var", values_to = "val") |>
    group_by(ig = ig_short, var) |> 
    summarize(
        net_agree = mean(as.integer(val) < 3, na.rm = TRUE) - mean(as.integer(val) > 3, na.rm = TRUE)
    )
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'ig'. You can override using the `.groups`
argument.
Show code 
t_job_sat |> 
    pivot_wider(names_from = ig, values_from = net_agree) |> 
    mutate(
        lab = case_when(
            var |> str_detect("advance") ~ "I have opportunities to advance", 
            var |> str_detect("overall") ~ "I am satisfied with my job", 
            var |> str_detect("precarity") ~ "I worry about losing my job"
        )
    ) |> 
    select(-var) |> 
    select(lab, everything()) |>  
    gt() |>

tbl_pathways <- d_long |>
    pivot_longer(
        matches("reached$"),
        names_pattern = "(.*)_reached$",
        names_to = "pathway_stage",

    )

2.4.2 Overall Satisfaction

Table 2.12 summarizes the distribution Net Promoter Scores (NPS) within each inclusion group. As measured by NPS, respondent satisfaction with employment services is quite low. In each inclusion group and in the sample overall, the proportion of respondents in the ‘Promoter’ category is lower than the proportion in the ‘Detractor’ category. The upshot is that, within and around this set of respondents, we would expect word-of-mouth to be a net negative influence on demand for employment services.

While this finding points to the existence of opportunities for improvement across the board, it is also worth noting that the distribution of NPS scores is not uniform across inclusion groups. Indigenous respondents are by far the least likely to be employment services ‘Promoters’ and the most likely to be ‘Detractors’. Individuals experiencing disability follow a similar pattern, though the difference from the sample averge (shown in the ‘Total’ row) is less pronounced.

Show code 
d_sat <- d_long |> 
    filter(engage_reached) |> 
    mutate(
        es_promoter = ux_nps_nps_group %in% "Promoter", 
        es_detractor = ux_nps_nps_group %in% "Detractor",
        es_nps_marginal = 100 * (es_promoter - es_detractor),
    ) |> 
    arrange(
        ig_short
    ) |> 
    mutate(
        ig_short = fct_inorder(ig_short)
    )

t_es_ovr <- d_sat |> 
    group_by(ig = inclusion_group_label) |> 
    summarize(
        nps = mean(es_nps_marginal),
        promoter = mean(es_promoter), 
        detractor = mean(es_detractor), 
    )


t_es_ovr |>
    ungroup() |> 
    gt() |> 
    gtExtras::gt_theme_538() |> 
    gtExtras::gt_color_box(
        columns = c(promoter, detractor),
        domain = c(0, 1),
        scale = 100,
        suffix = "%",
        palette = c("#0000FF", "#f2f2f2", "#ff4500")
    ) |> 
    tab_style(
        style = cell_fill(color = "gray95"), 
        locations = cells_body(
            columns = nps
        )
    ) |> 
    fmt_number(columns = nps, decimals = 0) |> 
    tab_footnote(
        "NPS is calculated as the difference between the proportion of respondents who are promoters and the proportion who are detractors."
    )

Table 2.13 shows NPS for members of each pair of inclusion groups.

2.4.3 Holistic Reflections

Table 2.14 summarizes the percentage of employment services clients who responded “Always” to a series of questions about their experiences with employment services.

Show code 
tbl_holistic_sum <- d_long |>
    filter(engage_reached) |>
    pivot_longer(
        matches("^ux_journey"),
        names_to = "var",
        values_to = "val"
    ) |>
    mutate(
        lab = unlist(labs[var]) |> str_remove("^.*? - ")
    ) |>
    filter(
        !is.na(val)

        scale = 100,
        suffix = "%",
        palette = c("#0000FF", "#f2f2f2", "#ff4500")
    )

Table 2.15 shows the full distribution of responses to holistic reflection questions within each inclusion group. The questions are designed to capture the respondent’s overall experience with employment services. The experiences about which they inquire can be broadly thought of as ‘table stakes’, meaning that they represent a kind of foundational, minimum level of service quality. It feels uncontroversial to suggest that employment services clients should always feel like they know what is happing with their cases, that each activity is productive, and that they are given a safe space in which to discuss their needs. However, among the respondents in this sample, these experiences unfortunately comprise a minority of the total.

Show code

2.4.5 Reflections on Making Progress

Table 2.18 summarizes the distribution of responses to questions about respondent experiences of codesigning and making progress in their plans for employment. These figures echo the trends observed above: newcomers, youth, and Indigenous clients disproprotionately feel that the employment services system does not communicate with them effectively, nor does it understand the goals and needs they express. Naturally, members of the same set of groups are less likely to report confidence in the effectiveness of the plan, and less likely to feel that it is responsive to their needs.

2.4.6 Reflections on Starting Employment

Table 2.19 summarizes the distribution of responses to questions about respondent experiences of starting employment as part of their employment services journies.
